explanation: 'ceb' is the ISO 639-3 code and common abbreviation for the Cebuano language; it is not a Cebuano word but is used to label the language in tags, filenames, and metadata.

A definite noun/topic marker in Cebuano placed before a noun or noun phrase to mark the subject or focus of the sentence. It roughly corresponds to 'the' but functions as a grammatical case/voice marker rather than a simple article.

A Cebuano marker of possibility or potentiality meaning 'may be,' 'could be,' or 'possible to become.' It is used before adjectives, verbs, or nouns to indicate something can happen or be the case (e.g., 'Mahimong ting-ulan' — 'It may rain').
A common conjunction meaning "and", used to link words, phrases, clauses, or sentences in Cebuano. It can also convey a sense of "also" or sequence (similar to "and then") depending on context.

A common Cebuano discourse particle (pronounced "ah") used to show surprise or emphasis, soften or reinforce statements/commands, or seek confirmation—similar to English "ah," "right?", or "you know" in informal speech.

A very common preposition used to mark location, direction, time, possession, or relationship between nouns; it corresponds to English words like 'in', 'at', 'to', 'of', or 'for' depending on context.

'i-' is a Cebuano verbal prefix that forms patient/object-focus verbs, often used for commands or causatives (e.g., 'Ihatag ang libro' = 'Give the book', 'Ibutang sa lamesa' = 'Put it on the table'). It indicates the action is directed at the following object.
Second-person singular pronoun in Cebuano used as the subject or for emphasis (e.g., 'Ikaw ang boss' — 'You are the boss'). It often appears as the unstressed form 'ka' after verbs or particles.
A proximal demonstrative pronoun meaning something close to the speaker; used like 'this' or 'this one', often in phrases such as 'kini nga [noun]' or as a stand-alone pronoun.
An existential/possessive marker meaning 'there is' or 'to have'; often contracted as 'aduna'y' and used to indicate existence or possession in Cebuano.

A grammatical linker or relativizer used to connect adjectives/adverbs to nouns or to introduce subordinate clauses; it often corresponds to English 'that' or 'which' and is frequently untranslated in natural English. It is required after modifiers in standard Cebuano but can be dropped in casual speech.

Most commonly a conjunction meaning "because" (e.g., Wala ko kay nagsakit ko = I didn't go because I was sick). It can also appear as a preposition before personal names to mark a recipient/possessor or link to a person in colloquial usage.
An imperative/form of the verb 'buhat' meaning 'to do' or 'to make'; commonly used to command or instruct someone ("Do it!"), and can also function as a verb meaning 'to do' in other contexts.
A third-person singular pronoun in Cebuano used to refer to a person or thing; it is gender-neutral and commonly functions as subject or object depending on context.
A prepositional phrase meaning 'with' or 'along with', used to indicate accompaniment or inclusion (e.g., 'uban sa akong amigo' = 'together with my friend').
A general negator in Cebuano used to negate verbs, adjectives, and clauses (e.g., "dili ko mokaon" = "I will not eat"); depending on context it can also mean "no" or express refusal.
A first-person plural pronoun used to refer to the speaker and others but excluding the addressee; contrasts with 'kita' which includes the listener.
A conjunction used to introduce contrast or contradiction, equivalent to English 'but' or 'however'. Common in both spoken and written Cebuano to present an exception or opposing idea.
A third-person plural pronoun used to refer to people or things as subject or object in Cebuano, equivalent to English "they" or "them".
A Cebuano verb meaning 'to tell' or 'to say to someone', used when instructing or relaying information (e.g., 'ingnon ko siya' = 'I'll tell him/her').
An interrogative pronoun used to ask about things or identify something (e.g., "Unsa ni?" — "What is this?").

A third-person singular possessive pronoun indicating ownership by someone or something; context determines whether it means 'his,' 'her,' or 'its.' It can also be used reflexively to mean 'one's own.'
A prepositional phrase meaning 'from,' indicating origin, source, or starting point; used before places, people, or times (e.g., 'gikan sa balay' = 'from the house').
A Cebuano verb meaning to walk; it is also commonly used to mean 'to go' or 'to leave' (e.g., the imperative 'Lakaw!' = 'Go!/Leave!'), and can function nominally as 'a walk.'

A coordinating conjunction used to present alternatives or choices (equivalent to English 'or'), commonly used in correlative pairs 'o ... o ...' for 'either ... or ...'; it can occasionally function as an interjection similar to 'oh'.
A prepositional phrase used to indicate means, method, or agency (e.g., 'pinaagi sa tubig' = 'by/through water' or 'pinaagi sa pagtudlo' = 'through teaching').

'Kuhaa' is the imperative or polite command form of the verb 'kuha' (to take/get), used to tell someone to take, fetch, or pick up something; context can make it mean 'get it', 'pick it up', or 'grab it'.

A first-person singular possessive pronoun in Cebuano used before nouns to indicate ownership or association (e.g., 'akong balay' = 'my house'). It can also appear as a determiner replacing 'ako' in possessive constructions.

A verb or modal indicating ability, permission, or possibility (equivalent to 'can', 'may', or 'become'); used to express that something can be done or may happen (e.g., mahimo ko = I can / it is possible).
Used to report speech or indicate manner—equivalent to 'said,' 'to say,' or 'like/as' in comparisons; often appears in phrases like 'ingon siya' (he/she said) or 'ingon nga' (that/which is said).
